parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The inability to fill the fuel tank to its full capacity can lead to frequent refueling, reduced fuel efficiency, and potentially environmental harm and vehicle emission control damage.
symptoms: The fuel tank can only be filled to 9-10 gallons
even when the gauge reads empty
despite the tank's advertised capacity of 14.5 gallons; the fuel pump handle/nozzle clicks off early
indicating the tank is not full; the vehicle's range is reduced

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the brake pedal to respond properly can lead to accidents, injuries, and damage to the vehicle, as the driver may not be able to stop the vehicle in time.
symptoms: The brake pedal requires excessive force to stop the vehicle
the brake pedal fails to respond when depressed
the brake pedal is depressed to the floorboard
the vehicle swerves or loses control.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the fuel pump handle can prevent the vehicle from being refueled, leaving the driver stranded and potentially causing safety risks.
symptoms: The fuel pump handle clicks off inadvertently while attempting to refuel the vehicle
preventing the vehicle from being refueled.

parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Fuel Leak and Fuel Sending Unit Failure
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The fuel leak and fuel sending unit failure can cause fuel to leak onto the floor, creating a fire hazard and potential safety risks.
symptoms: Fuel leaking onto the floor under the fuel filler neck

parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Inaccurate Fuel Tank Capacity and Fuel Gauge Readings
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The inaccurate fuel tank capacity and fuel gauge readings can cause drivers to run out of fuel unexpectedly, leading to safety risks and potentially leaving them stranded.
symptoms: The fuel tank capacity is listed as 14.5 gallons but can only fill to approximately 9 gallons
the "miles to empty" reading on the fuel gauge is inaccurate
the actual gas in the tank is much lower than the vehicle's reading.
